  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- First formal regulations requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Limited initial scope and enforcement\n\n2. International Development\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created global standards and recommendations\n- Developed comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) guidelines\n\n3. Key Legislation Milestones\n- 1992: EU First Money Laundering Directive\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n\n4. Modern Developments\n- Expanded coverage to cryptocurrencies\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- More rigorous beneficial ownership transparency\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Machine learning and AI-assisted detection\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Stronger cross-border collaboration\n- Comprehensive risk-based approaches\n- More sophisticated technological detection methods\n- Focus on terrorist financing prevention\n- Greater regulatory complexity\n\nThe legislative landscape continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
